Federal officials, including House Majority Whip Steve Scalise and Senate Finance Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, have expressed support for President Trump's renegotiated trade deal with Mexico. They believe the deal will benefit American workers and modernize NAFTA, the largest free trade zone in the world. State officials, such as Iowa Governor Kim Reynolds and Nebraska Governor Pete Ricketts, have also praised the agreement, as it will bring more certainty to farmers and expand trade opportunities. Trade associations and labor unions, including the American Farm Bureau Federation and the American Iron and Steel Institute, have also voiced their support for the deal. Overall, there is optimism that the agreement will be beneficial for the American economy and workers.